# Backend Standards (Node.js)

## Error Handling

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Silent failure
try {
  await dbQuery();
} catch (e) {}

// ✅ GOOD - Proper logging and user-friendly error
try {
  await dbQuery();
} catch (e) {
  logger.error('Database query failed', { error: e });
  throw new DatabaseError('Unable to fetch data', { cause: e });
}
```

## Input Validation

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - No validation
app.post('/api/booking', async (req, res) => {
  const booking = await createBooking(req.body);
  res.json(booking);
});

// ✅ GOOD - Validated inputs
app.post('/api/booking', validate(bookingSchema), async (req, res) => {
  const sanitized = sanitizeInput(req.body);
  const booking = await createBooking(sanitized);
  res.json(booking);
});
```

## Environment Variables

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Hardcoded
const apiKey = 'sk_live_12345';

// ✅ GOOD - Environment variable with validation
const apiKey = process.env.API_KEY;
if (!apiKey) throw new Error('API_KEY not configured');
```

## External Services — Fail Fast (MANDATORY)

Never silently swallow failures from email, SMS, or payment providers. If a service call fails, the caller must know.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — silent failure, caller thinks email was sent
if (!apiKey) {
  console.log('No API key, skipping email');
  return; // caller has no idea email wasn't sent
}

// ✅ GOOD — throw so caller can handle it
if (!apiKey || apiKey === 'your_placeholder_here') {
  throw new Error('Email provider not configured');
}
```

In development/test without keys, log the OTP/token to console but make it obvious. In production, always throw.

## Deployment

- Use multi-stage Dockerfiles (builder stage with devDeps for `tsc`, final stage with prod deps only)
- `CMD` must be `node dist/index.js`, never `npm run dev`
- Backend reads `PORT` from env (Railway sets it automatically)

## Required Practices

- Use async/await over callbacks
- Implement proper logging (Winston, Pino)
- Rate limiting on all public endpoints
- JWT token validation on protected routes
- Database connection pooling
- Graceful shutdown handlers
